<br>
My character (and I'll call him Jack because I haven't come up with a decent name yet) is a former Paladin of Erudin who heard the calling of the Faceless. He'd spent most of his life preserving the unstable peacetime that Erudin knows today, but recently Jack grew tired of allowing his enemies to roam freely in order to prevent war. He lived for battle, and had always enjoyed the expressions of terror on the faces of his foes, which remained there long after they'd had their last breath. He had an undeniable thirst for this fear and the blood that came along with it.<br>
<br>
Jack realized that he wasn't meant to be a Paladin, but didn't know how he became one. Unknown to him (and anyone but the High Men of Erudin) were his origins. One rainy morning, many seasons ago, a broken raft drifted to a small alcove between Erudin and Paineel. On it were many mutilated adult bodies and a small bundle wrapped within a stained blanket. Fishermen at the shore had sent a page to Erudin detailing the found child; but when the small troupe of High Men arrived to transport the young Erudite back to loyalist society, a small band of Heretic spies had just overcome the last of the seafarer's and were ready to steal away into the woods with the child.<br>
<br>
A small battle ensued, with the loyalists surviving. A few days later, a researcher approached the council of High Men with a prophecy he'd found in the city library. It essentially described the arrival of the child, and foretold that he would grow to be a great crusader of fear. They did not want to kill the child, but they did not want him to become evil either. They decided that they must instill in him the virtues of The Tranquil, and have him live as holy of a life as they could. They did not realize that it was impossible to alter destiny.<br>
<br>
Later, after Jack's destructive intentions were discovered, he was arrested and prepared to be executed. He was escorted by a small team of guards to The Hole, but before he was thrown in, a brief vision came to him from the sky. A young man and a young woman were shown to him, both Erudites, but they appeared to be burning alive. The vision faded after only a moment, but the guards had seen it too. He used the opportunity to overcome his captors and cast them into certain death.<br>
<br>
Quellious stripped Jack of his clerical abilities, but Cazic-Thule allowed the disowned Paladin to worship him instead, and this was told to Jack by whispers into his mind. He approached the city of Paineel, shackles and all, and was quickly accosted. His new-found father spoke through him at this critical moment, and after much convincing he was allowed to begin his studies at the Temple of the Fell Blade.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
I was thinking that the people Jack saw in the sky were his parents, who were somehow connected to the old Erudite Heretics. They were early Heretics, back when the loyalists far outnumbered them (do they still?), and had fled capture by sailing across the ocean to Qeynos with loyalists close behind. They were caught between the Paladins of Marr at Qeynos and the Erudites behind them, and the parents were executed. The loyalists took what they believed to be an uncorrupted infant back with them, but between Qeynos and the final destination of the raft, baby Jack somehow took upon powers that were not entirely of his own and slaughtered the others.<br>
<br>
Does that sound okay?<br>
<br>
